Azure Monitor is the unified observability platform for Azure. It collects, analyses, and acts on telemetry from your Azure resources, applications, virtual machines, containers, and on-premises infrastructure. The two primary data stores inside Azure Monitor are Metrics — lightweight numerical time-series data stored for 93 days — and Log Analytics — structured log data queryable with K-Q-L and retained for up to two years. On top of these data stores, Azure Monitor provides Alerts to notify you when conditions are met, Workbooks for interactive reporting, and Dashboards for at-a-glance operational views.

Let us start with Azure Monitor Metrics.

Metrics are numerical values collected at regular intervals — typically every minute — from Azure resources. Examples include C-P-U percentage, network bytes in and out, request count, queue depth, and disk I-O-P-S. There are three types of metrics. Platform metrics are automatically collected by Azure from all resources at no cost — every V-M, storage account, and App Service reports these without any configuration. Custom metrics are emitted by your application code through the Azure Monitor S-D-K, and you are charged per metric series. Prometheus metrics are scraped from A-K-S clusters or Azure Monitor Managed Prometheus and are charged per sample.

Metrics Explorer in the Azure portal lets you plot any metric over a time range, apply aggregations such as average, minimum, maximum, sum, or count, and split the data by dimensions. Dimensions are additional properties on a metric that let you break it down further. For example, a storage account's transaction count metric has dimensions for response type and A-P-I name, so you can see exactly which A-P-I operations are generating traffic or errors.

Platform metrics are stored for 93 days. For longer retention, you use Diagnostic Settings to route metrics to a Log Analytics workspace or a Storage Account.

Now let us look at Diagnostic Settings.

Diagnostic Settings control where a resource's telemetry is sent. Every Azure resource supports configuring a diagnostic setting with up to four destinations: a Log Analytics workspace for K-Q-L querying, a Storage Account for cheap long-term archival, an Event Hub for streaming to a S-I-E-M or third-party tool like Splunk or Datadog, and partner solution integrations.

There are two categories of telemetry routed by Diagnostic Settings. The Activity Log records all control-plane operations on Azure resources — who created, modified, or deleted what, and when. It is the answer to the question: who changed this resource? The Activity Log is retained for 90 days by default and can be sent to a Log Analytics workspace for longer retention and querying. Categories include Administrative for resource changes, Security for Entra I-D events, Service Health for Azure outage notifications, and Policy for Azure Policy compliance results.

Resource Logs — formerly called Diagnostic Logs — capture data-plane operations happening inside a resource. Examples include every query executed against Azure S-Q-L, every secret read or written in Key Vault, H-T-T-P access logs for App Service, and read/write/delete operations on Storage Accounts. Resource logs are not collected by default — you must explicitly enable them in a Diagnostic Setting.

Now let us look at Log Analytics and K-Q-L.

Log Analytics is the query engine and storage backend for Azure Monitor logs. You write queries in K-Q-L, which stands for Kusto Query Language — a powerful, read-only query language designed for large-scale telemetry analysis. A Log Analytics workspace is the container for log data. The key design decision is whether to use a centralised workspace shared across your organisation, or distributed workspaces per team or region. Centralised workspaces simplify cross-resource querying, reduce per-gigabyte ingestion costs, and make it easier to apply consistent retention policies. Interactive retention can be configured from 30 to 730 days, and an archive tier extends storage up to 12 years at lower cost.

K-Q-L queries follow a pipe-based syntax where you start with a table name and chain operators using the pipe character. The where operator filters rows. The project operator selects or renames columns. The extend operator adds computed columns. The summarize operator aggregates data — common aggregation functions include count, avg, sum, percentile, and dcount for distinct count. The bin function rounds values into time buckets — for example 5-minute buckets. The join operator joins two tables. The render operator visualises results as a time chart, bar chart, or pie chart. And the ago function expresses relative time — for example ago of 1 hour or ago of 7 days.

A typical query might look like this: start with the requests table from Application Insights, filter for events in the last hour and where success is false, summarize the failure count by request name and result code, and order by failure count descending to get the top failing operations.

Now let us look at Application Insights.

Application Insights is the A-P-M, or Application Performance Monitoring, component of Azure Monitor. You add the Application Insights S-D-K to your application — or use automatic instrumentation for supported runtimes — and it begins collecting telemetry automatically. It captures requests with rate, duration, and success or failure; dependency calls to S-Q-L, Redis, and downstream H-T-T-P A-P-Is with latency and failure rate; unhandled exceptions with full stack traces; page views from browser clients; custom events and custom metrics you instrument in your code; log traces correlated with requests; and availability results from synthetic ping tests run from global Points of Presence.

Workspace-based Application Insights is the current recommended mode. It stores all telemetry in a Log Analytics workspace, enabling you to write K-Q-L queries that join application telemetry with infrastructure logs in the same workspace. For example, you can correlate a spike in V-M C-P-U with an increase in application response times in a single query.

Distributed tracing is one of Application Insights' most powerful features. A correlation I-D is generated for each incoming request and propagated in H-T-T-P headers through all downstream service calls. Application Insights collects the telemetry from each service and assembles a complete end-to-end trace. The Application Map visualises all services and their dependencies as a graph, colour-coding nodes by failure rate and response time — making it straightforward to identify which service is the bottleneck or failure point in a distributed system.

Live Metrics streams real-time request rate, failure rate, and active server count in a one-second refresh. This is particularly useful for watching a deployment roll out — you can see immediately if the new version is producing errors.

To control costs, Application Insights supports adaptive sampling, which automatically adjusts the percentage of requests that are sampled to keep ingestion near a target volume. Fixed-rate sampling sends a consistent percentage of all requests. Ingestion sampling is applied after data arrives at the backend and can be configured without changing application code.

Now let us look at Azure Monitor Alerts.

Alerts notify you or trigger automated remediation when a condition is met. An alert rule has four parts: the scope — the resource or resources being monitored; the condition — a signal and threshold; the severity from zero for critical to four for verbose; and an action group that defines what happens when the alert fires.

There are six signal types. Metric alerts fire when a metric crosses a threshold — for example C-P-U exceeding 80% average for 5 minutes. Log alerts fire when a K-Q-L query run against Log Analytics returns results meeting a condition — for example more than 10 errors in the last 15 minutes. Activity log alerts fire on specific control-plane events — for example when a virtual machine is deleted. Resource Health alerts fire when a resource's availability changes — for example a V-M becomes unavailable. Service Health alerts fire during Azure outage notifications. And Smart Detection in Application Insights uses machine learning to automatically detect unusual failure rate increases or performance degradations.

For metric alerts, you configure the aggregation type — average, min, max, total, or count — the comparison operator, the threshold value, how often the condition is evaluated, and the time window over which the metric is aggregated. Instead of a static threshold, you can use dynamic thresholds, which use machine learning to learn the normal pattern of the metric including daily and weekly seasonality. Dynamic thresholds only fire on genuine anomalies, significantly reducing false positive alerts compared to static thresholds.

An action group defines what happens when an alert fires. Multiple alert rules can share the same action group. Actions include email, S-M-S, push notification to the Azure mobile app, and voice call for human notification. Webhooks call any H-T-T-P-S endpoint. Logic Apps trigger a workflow. Azure Functions trigger a function for automated remediation — for example restarting a service or scaling out a V-M-S-S. Event Hub sends the alert payload for downstream processing. I-T-S-M connectors create tickets in ServiceNow or Jira. And Azure Automation Runbooks execute pre-written remediation scripts.

Alert processing rules — formerly called Action Rules — let you suppress alerts during planned maintenance windows, or add additional action groups to all alerts matching a scope without modifying each individual alert rule. This is useful for temporarily silencing alerts across an entire resource group during a deployment.

Let us briefly cover the Azure Monitor Agent and related services.

The Azure Monitor Agent, or A-M-A, is the current recommended agent for collecting data from virtual machines. It replaces three legacy agents that previously served different roles. The A-M-A is configured through Data Collection Rules — J-S-O-N-based resources that define what data to collect, such as performance counters, Windows Event Log, or Syslog, and where to send it — one or more Log Analytics workspaces or Azure Monitor Metrics. Data Collection Rules are assigned to individual V-Ms, resource groups, or subscriptions.

V-M Insights uses the Azure Monitor Agent to provide out-of-the-box dashboards showing V-M performance — C-P-U, memory, disk, and network trends — and a dependency map that visualises all processes running on the V-M and the T-C-P connections they make to other services. Enabling V-M Insights is a single-click operation in the portal.

Container Insights monitors A-K-S clusters by deploying the Azure Monitor Agent as a DaemonSet on every node. It collects pod logs, node resource metrics, and container performance data into a Log Analytics workspace, with built-in dashboards for cluster health, node resource utilisation, and pod restarts.

Workbooks are interactive reports that combine text, K-Q-L queries, metric charts, and parameter pickers into a single document. They are more powerful than dashboards for deep analysis — you can drill from a summary view into per-resource details, add time range or subscription selectors, and share workbook templates across teams. Dashboards are simpler pinned panels for at-a-glance operational views. Azure Managed Grafana provides a fully managed Grafana instance with built-in Azure Monitor and Prometheus data sources for teams that prefer Grafana's visualisation capabilities.

To summarise. Azure Monitor is the single observability platform across all Azure resources. Metrics provide near-real-time numerical telemetry for 93 days — use Metrics Explorer for ad-hoc analysis and metric alerts for proactive notification. Diagnostic Settings route resource logs and metrics to a Log Analytics workspace, Storage Account, or Event Hub. The Activity Log records all control-plane changes and is the audit trail for your Azure environment. Log Analytics with K-Q-L enables powerful ad-hoc investigation and log alerts. Application Insights provides end-to-end A-P-M with distributed tracing, dependency mapping, and availability monitoring. Use dynamic thresholds in alerts to reduce false positives. Build action groups with automated remediation using Azure Functions or Automation Runbooks. And use V-M Insights and Container Insights for out-of-the-box dashboards for virtual machine and A-K-S workloads.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure Key Vault and Managed Identities — the services that protect secrets, certificates, and keys, and enable applications to authenticate without storing credentials.
